# Amicus Brief

Produce or evaluate U.S. appellate amicus briefs that add a distinct, rule-compliant perspective to the court.

# Prerequisites

1. Case docket and parties’ briefs.  
2. Client or organization interest and authority to submit amicus.  
3. Governing rules, local court requirements, and filing deadlines.  
4. Relevant record materials and supporting evidence.  
5. Consent from parties or leave of court as required.

# Output Structure / Process

| Mode     | Description                                             | Core Steps                                                                                       |
|----------|---------------------------------------------------------|------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|
| Drafting | Prepare compliant draft amicus brief                     | 1. Verify prerequisites 2. Follow formatting rules 3. Include required sections 4. Apply citations and disclosures 5. Review compliance checklist |
| Analysis | Evaluate existing amicus brief for quality and compliance | 1. Assess novelty and relevance 2. Verify authority and interest 3. Check for disclosure and rule compliance 4. Review legal analysis and structure |

## Drafting Checklist

- [ ] Confirm adherence to FRAP 29 and Supreme Court Rule 37 (see Guidelines).  
- [ ] Include identity and interest of amicus and party supported.  
- [ ] Obtain and document consent or court leave.  
- [ ] Disclose authorship, funding sources, and affiliations as required.  
- [ ] Ensure no new issues are introduced unless permitted and framed properly.  
- [ ] Cite authorities with Bluebook format.  
- [ ] Comply with word/page limits (typically 6,500 words for amicus under FRAP 29(b)) [VERIFY].  
- [ ] Include required sections and follow court-specific formatting.

## Analysis Checklist

- [ ] Verify brief presents a unique and non-duplicative perspective.  
- [ ] Confirm interest and authority of amicus party.  
- [ ] Check disclosure of funding, authorship, and consent status.  
- [ ] Assess alignment with supported party’s position without improper new issues.  
- [ ] Evaluate citation quality and legal authority.  
- [ ] Ensure conformity to relevant court rules and deadlines.

# Template Outline

```
[Cover/Caption Page]

Statement of Interest  
Statement of Consent or Leave to File  
Summary of Argument  
Argument (with clear headings)  
Conclusion  
Certificate of Compliance (word count verification)  
Certificate of Service  
Appendix (if applicable)
```

# Guidelines

- Always verify and follow the specific appellate court’s local rules.  
- FRAP 29 governs federal appellate amicus briefs; Supreme Court Rule 37 applies to SCOTUS filings.  
- Consent from all parties or leave of court is generally required before filing.  
- Disclose all financial support, authorship, or funding sources per FRAP 29(a)(4)(E) and SCOTUS Rule 37.6.  
- Avoid raising new legal issues not presented by the parties unless clearly permitted; frame any new issues in support of existing questions.  
- Comply with applicable word or page limits; typically 6,500 words for amicus briefs under FRAP 29(b) [VERIFY].  
- Include corporate disclosure statements where applicable (see FRAP 26.1 and related rules).  
- Cite all authorities following Bluebook standards.  
- Check for deadlines, filing methods (e.g., ECF), and certificate of service requirements.  
- Protect confidential or sealed information; do not reveal information outside the official record unless authorized.  
- When citing extra-record materials, limit use to policy or legislative facts and clearly label as such.  
- Tailor briefing to appellate context and jurisdictional nuances.  
- Filing timing is typically within 7 days after principal brief of supported party is filed [VERIFY].

# Rule Checks

| Rule or Requirement                       | What to Confirm                                             |
|------------------------------------------|--------------------------------------------------------------|
| FRAP 29                                  | Governs federal appellate amicus briefs                      |
| Supreme Court Rule 37                     | Governs SCOTUS amicus briefs                                 |
| FRAP 29(a)(4)(E) & SCOTUS Rule 37.6     | Disclosure of authorship, funding, and affiliations          |
| FRAP 29(b)                               | Word limit of 6,500 words for amicus briefs [VERIFY]         |
| Filing deadlines                         | Typically within 7 days of principal brief [VERIFY]          |
| Consent vs. leave of court               | Requirement depending on court and case                      |
| Corporate Disclosure (FRAP 26.1)         | Disclosure statements for corporate amici                    |

# Citations

- Federal Rules of Appellate Procedure Rule 29  
- Supreme Court Rule 37  
- FRAP 29(a)(4)(E) disclosure requirements  
- FRAP 29(b) word limits [VERIFY]  
- SCOTUS Rule 37.6 disclosure rules

Use this skill to draft or analyze amicus briefs ensuring compliance with U.S. appellate procedures and effective presentation of non-party interests.
